<h1>MySQL Workbench</h1>
<h2>Objectives:</h2>
<ol><li>Introduction to MySQL Workbench</li><li>Make first queries in MySQL workbench</li></ol>
<h2>What is MySQL Workbench?</h2>
<p>
 MySQL Workbench is just a Graphical User Interface (GUI) for us to interact with <strong>MySQL</strong>, one of the most popular relational databases in the world - through SQL commands. It is not necessary to use a GUI. We could interact with our MySQL databases through the terminal, but the GUI makes it much easier to see our data and create new databases.</p>
<h2>Why MySQL Workbench?</h2>
<p>
 We use MySQL Workbench when we are interacting with our databases because it allow us to directly make SQL queries. It also has a great interface where we can map out our tables and establish relationships between them.</p>
<p>Click on (or stay clicked on) the database symbol at the top left, and open your Local instance. You will need to put in your password, which was "root" based on our installation instruction.</p>

<h2>Querying the database</h2>
<p>Before starting to query your database, you can open a new query tab by going to file &gt; new query tab. You can save it by then going to file &gt; Save Script As.</p>
<p>Once you have multiple databases, you will need to make sure you are using the desired database.  You can either click on the database name in the schemas tab or indicate the desired database with USE. We are going to complete our first query which is simply to see all of the tables in the database.  </p>
<pre>USE world;
SHOW tables;</pre>
<figure><img src="data:image/png;base64,"></figure>
<p><br></p>
<p>Now that this database is loaded into MySQL Workbench, we can use SQL queries directly in the workspace. This can be easier and faster than using SQLAlchemy in Python as we have practiced earlier. The queries themselves, are the same.</p>
<p>Try writing a query to select all information from the cities table.</p>
<pre>SELECT * 
FROM cities;
</pre>
